To maximize regenerative braking, which is necessary in steep mountain terrain, charge to 80% or less. Tap the info icon to learn more.

It's important to charge your battery to 80% or less if your route includes long, steep descents. This is especially true when towing a trailer, which puts additional stress on your vehicle's braking system. Charging below 80% helps preserve long-term battery health and lets you charge the battery with free energy from regenerative braking.

Regenerative braking supplements your vehicle's conventional brakes, especially when going downhill. If the battery is charged above 80%, regenerative braking will be limited or unavailable, and your conventional brakes may overheat and fade on long, steep descents.

See your Owner's Manual for more information.
Charging for Battery Health and Vehicle Safety

It's important to charge your battery to 80% for daily use. This helps promote battery health and ensures optimal regenerative braking performance, which helps increase efficiency. For longer trips, you can adjust your charge above 80% for extended range. 

If your route includes steep mountain terrain, it's important to charge to 80% or less for full regenerative braking.

See your Owner's Manual for more information.

When on, you\'ll receive alerts when the combined weight of your vehicle and trailer may exceed the vehicle\'s Gross Combined Weight Rating.

After you begin a trip, the system uses engine-torque data to estimate the combined weight of your vehicle and trailer. If the estimated weight could exceed the vehicle's Gross Combined Weight Rating (GCWR), the system will alert you. Estimated weights may vary from actual weights. The alert does not measure the loaded weight of your vehicle or trailer.

The alert will not activate unless:
• the feature is on in the Trailering application
• there are enough acceleration events for the system to estimate the combined vehicle and trailer weight
• the estimated weight may exceed the vehicle’s GCWR.

If you see the alert, stop the vehicle safely and check whether the vehicle and trailer are overloaded using a scale.

Warning:
• Always determine the actual weights of the loaded truck and trailer on a scale before beginning a trip.
• Never use the GCW Alert to determine whether the vehicle and trailer are properly loaded or overloaded.
• Do not drive with an overloaded vehicle or trailer. Death, serious injury or property damage could occur.

The GCWR is only one of the load ratings applicable to your vehicle and trailer. The GCW Alert does not estimate whether:
• the vehicle alone exceeds the Gross Vehicle Weight Rating (GVWR)
• the rear-axle weight exceeds Rear Gross Axle Weight Rating (RGAWR)
• the trailer exceeds the Trailer Weight Rating (TWR)
• the trailer tongue weight exceeds the Max Tongue Weight Rating

Always verify that the weight of the vehicle, vehicle cargo, trailer, trailer cargo and trailer tongue are below these load ratings.
The Gross Combined Weight (GCW) Alert warns you when the estimated vehicle and trailer weight exceeds your Gross Combined Weight Rating (GCWR).

The Gross Combined Weight Rating is the max allowed combined weight of your vehicle and trailer. This weight includes passengers and cargo being hauled.\n\nYour GCWR can be found on the Trailering Information label located in driver’s side door jamb.
How does the GCW Alert work?

When on, the system uses propulsion system torque data from your trip to estimate your vehicle and trailer\'s combined weight. If that estimated weight exceeds the GCWR, you\'ll be alerted.\n\nThese estimated weights may vary from your actual combined weight. This alert does not measure the loaded weight of your vehicle or trailer. The alert becomes active once there are enough acceleration events to estimate the combined weight.

Before your trip, determine the actual weight of your loaded vehicle and trailer on a scale. Never use the GCW Alert to determine if the vehicle and trailer are properly loaded or overloaded.\n\nDo not drive with an overloaded vehicle and/or trailer. Death, serious injury, or property damage could occur. If you see the alert, stop your vehicle safely and use a scale to check if the vehicle and trailer are overloaded.

The GCWR is only one of the load ratings applicable to your vehicle and trailer. The GCW Alert does not estimate whether:
• The vehicle alone exceeds the Gross Vehicle Weight Rating (GVWR)
• The rear-axle weight exceeds Rear Gross Axle Weight Rating (RGAWR)
• The trailer exceeds the Trailer Weight Rating (TWR)
• The trailer tongue weight exceeds the Max Tongue Weight Rating

Curb Weight (%1$s) is the weight of the vehicle without driver, passengers, cargo, or accessories.

Gross Combined Weight is the total weight of the vehicle and trailer combination, including the weight of the driver, passengers, fuel, optional equipment, and cargo. This should be below the Gross Combined Weight Rating (%1$s).

Gross Vehicle Weight is the total weight of the vehicle, driver, passengers, fuel, optional equipment, cargo in the vehicle, trailer hitch, and the trailer tongue weight. This weight should be below the Gross Vehicle Weight Rating (%1$s).
Max payload (%1$s) is the most weight your vehicle can carry, including driver, passengers, cargo, and trailer tongue weight. If you\'re towing a heavy trailer load, your payload should be less.
Rear Gross Axle Weight Rating (%1$s) is the most weight the rear axle can carry. The cargo should be evenly distributed over the axle.

How will you set up your tire pressure sensors?

You can set up the Trailer Tire Pressure Monitoring sensors with a special tool or manually. Choose Set Up with Tool if you have a sensor tool. The setup for each sensor normally takes about 10 seconds. The system will time out if a sensor takes longer than 2 minutes.
Deflate or inflate each trailer tire to manually set up the sensors. Make sure each tire\'s pressure is at the appropriate level when you\'re done.
If you have a sensor tool, activate it near the valve stem of each trailer tire to set up the sensors.
How do I set up the sensors?

Follow the steps below to set up each sensor. You have 2 minutes per sensor.

Follow the steps below to learn each sensor. You have 2 minutes per sensor.

1. Press Start Setup.

2. Go to trailer tire %1$d.

3. Activate the tool near the valve stem and hold it there until horn chirps (about 10 seconds).

4. Repeat step 3 for each tire in the order shown.
3. Inflate or deflate tire until horn chirps (about 10 seconds)\n4. Repeat step 3 for each tire in the order shown

The Trailer Tire Pressure Monitoring System must learn the location of the installed tire sensors to show the correct air pressure and temperature for each tire.

This normally takes up to 10 seconds per sensor. If a sensor takes longer than 2 minutes to set up, the system will time out and no sensor locations will be saved.

You must repeat the setup process when you:
•Install a spare tire
•Rotate tires
•Replace or add new sensors

Follow these steps to set up the sensors:

1. Tap Start Setup on the Sensor Setup screen. The horn will chirp twice and the driver side front trailer tire will highlight on the screen.

2. Go to the driver side front trailer tire.

3. Inflate or deflate tire until the horn chirps and lights flash. Do not exceed the maximum inflation pressure found on the tire sidewalls.

4. Move to the next tire and repeat step 3 for each sensor. The horn will chirp twice when you finish all the sensors. Make sure to re-adjust tire pressure to the recommended level when you complete the process.

5. Complete the setup inside your vehicle.

The Trailer Tire Pressure Monitoring System must learn the location of the installed tire sensors to show correct air pressure and temperature for each tire.

The process normally takes around 10 seconds per sensor. If a sensor takes longer than 2 minutes to set up, the system will time out and no sensor locations will be saved.

*You must repeat the setup process when you:
•Install a spare tire
•Rotate tires
•Replace or add new sensors

Follow these steps to set up sensors:

1. Press Start on the Set Up Sensors screen. The horn chirps twice and the Setup Active screen appears on the radio.

2. Go to the driver side front trailer tire.

3. Activate the tool near the valve stem until the horn chirps and lights flash.

4. Move to the next tire and repeat step 3 for each sensor. The horn chirps twice when you finish all the sensors.

5. Return to your vehicle to complete the setup.

The Trailer Tire Pressure Monitoring System must learn the location of the installed tire sensors to show the correct air pressure and temperature for each tire.

This normally takes up to 10 seconds per sensor. If a sensor takes longer than 2 minutes to set up, the system will time out and no sensor locations will be saved.

4. Move to the next tire and repeat step 3 for each sensor. The horn will chirp twice when you finish all the sensors.

5. Complete the setup inside your vehicle.

It\'s important to charge your vehicle\'s battery to 80% or less for daily driving or routes that include long, steep descents. This is especially true when towing a trailer, which puts additional stress on your vehicle\'s braking system. Charging below 80% helps preserve long-term battery health and lets you charge the battery with free energy from regenerative braking.\nRegenerative braking supplements your vehicle\'s conventional brakes, especially when going downhill. If the battery is charged above 80%, regenerative braking will be limited or unavailable, and your conventional brakes may overheat and fade on long, steep descents.\nSee your Owner\'s Manual for more information.
To help preserve your battery and enable regenerative braking, which is necessary in steep mountain terrain, charge to 80% or less. Tap the info icon to learn more.

Follow the steps in this tutorial to properly and safely back a trailer into the water. Select Next to start.
Backing a Trailer into the Water

Prior to launching a boat, make sure to check off all tasks in the At Home and Boat Ramp Staging Area checklists. This will help you be prepared to launch your boat quickly and safely while being considerate of others at the boat ramp.

Have all passengers exit the vehicle before backing onto the sloped part of the ramp. Lower the driver and passenger side windows before backing onto the ramp. This will provide a means of escape in the unlikely event the vehicle slides into the water.

If the boat launch surface is slippery, have the driver remain in the vehicle with the brake pedal applied while the boat is being launched. The boat launch can be especially slippery at low tide when part of the ramp was previously submerged at high tide. Do not back onto the ramp to launch the boat if you are not sure the vehicle can maintain traction.

Do not move the vehicle if someone is in the path of the trailer. Some parts of the trailer might be underwater and not visible to people who are assisting in launching the boat.

Disconnect the wiring to the trailer before backing it into the water to prevent damage to the electrical circuits. Reconnect the writing to the trailer after removing it from the water.

If the trailer has electric brakes that function while it is submerged, it might help to leave the electrical trailer connector attached to maintain trailer brake functionality while on the boat ramp.

Also, if the trailer has lights that function when it is submerged, it is okay to leave the electrical trailer connector attached.

Once you have completed each checklist, approach the boat ramp. Position your vehicle so you can back the trailer down the boat ramp.\n\nPut your vehicle in 4WD and change the Drive Mode to Terrain (if equipped). This will help you with traction and handling as you back the trailer into the water. Terrain Mode will automatically apply the brakes for enhanced control on slippery boat ramps.
Slowly back down the boat ramp as straight as possible until the boat is floating, but no further than necessary.
Slowly back down the boat ramp until the boat is floating, but no further than necessary.
Back the Trailer into the Water

Press and hold the brake pedal, and shift into Park (P).

If necessary, have someone place chocks under the front wheels of the vehicle prior to shifting vehicle to Park (P).

Then, apply the electric park brake to ensure vehicle does not move backward into the water.

Tie the boat to a nearby dock or have a person hold the boat once it's in the water so that it does not float away. When the boat is secure, disconnect it from the trailer.

Once the boat is clear from the trailer, drive your vehicle out of the water and back up the boat ramp. Make sure your trailer connections are properly secure so that they do not drag on the ground.

 Park your vehicle and trailer in the designated parking area.

Once the boat driver is ready, disconnect the boat from the trailer. Make sure the boat is clear from the trailer, then drive your vehicle out of the water and back up the boat ramp. Park your vehicle and trailer in designated parking area.
Follow the steps in this tutorial to properly and safely pull a trailer from the water. Select Next to start.
Pulling a Trailer from the Water

Disconnect the wiring to the trailer before backing it into the water to prevent damage to the electrical circuits. Reconnect the wiring to the trailer after removing it from the water.

If the trailer has electric brakes that function while it is submerged, it might help to leave the electrical trailer connector attached to maintain trailer brake functionality while on the boat ramp.

Also, if the trailer has lights that function when it is submerged, it is okay to leave the electrical trailer connector attached.

Approach the boat ramp. Position your vehicle so you can back the trailer down the ramp.\n\nPut your vehicle in 4WD and change the Drive Mode to Terrain (if equipped). This will help you with traction and handling as you back the trailer into the water. Terrain Mode will automatically apply the brakes for enhanced control on slippery boat ramps.
Slowly back down the boat ramp to position the trailer in the water, just far enough so the boat can be maneuvered onto the trailer.
Back the Trailer into the Water

If necessary, make sure the boat motor is raised high enough to prevent damage to the boat’s propellor. \n\nThen, align boat with trailer and carefully maneuver boat onto the trailer. Connect the boat to the trailer when boat is within reach of the connection point.

If necessary, make sure the boat motor is raised high enough to prevent damage to the boat’s propellor. \n\nThen, carefully maneuver boat onto the trailer. Connect the boat to the trailer when boat is within reach of the connection point.

Once the boat is connected, slowly pull the trailer from the water.\n\nOnce the vehicle and trailer have been driven from the sloped part of the boat ramp, the vehicle can be shifted from 4WD. Shift into the Drive Mode that is appropriate for the road conditions.

If the vehicle tires begin to spin and the vehicle begins to slide toward the water, remove your foot from the accelerator pedal and apply the brake pedal. Seek help to have the vehicle towed up the ramp.

If the vehicle tires begin to spin and the vehicle begins to slide toward the water, remove your foot from the accelerator pedal and apply the brake pedal. Seek help to have the vehicle towed up the ramp.

Once the vehicle and trailer are clear from ramp, drive to the designated parking area to secure boat to the trailer with transom tiedown straps.

Plug in the electrical connector for the trailer lights and electric brakes.

Check the boat for any damage and secure loose items left in the boat such as fishing gear or tow toys. Lower or remove any tall parts of the boat that could be damaged during travel by trees or overpasses.

Once the vehicle and trailer are clear from ramp, drive to the designated parking area to secure boat to the trailer with transom tiedown straps.

Plug in the electrical connector for the trailer lights and electric brakes.

Driving faster than a tire\'s speed rating can cause tires to heat up and fail. Tires are designed to be driven briefly at their speed rating with maximum load. Tires are not designed to be driven over their speed rating.
What is the Tire Speed Alert?

Old tires can be dangerous regardless of tread depth and lack of visual dry rot / cracks. Tires deteriorate with age, even if you don\'t use them. Either way, the rubber becomes brittle which can cause failure. When storing your trailer, make sure the tires are not in direct sunlight (UV light oxidizes the rubber, causing the tires to rot). The best ways to protect your tires from dry rot is to cover and/or elevate them off the ground.

You\'ll receive an alert when your trailer tires reach 6 years of age. At that time, visit a tire professional to check if your tires need to be replaced. If not, you can snooze the reminder until a later date.\n\nTurn this feature on and off in Tires > Settings.

Old tires can be dangerous regardless of tread depth and lack of visual dry rot / cracks. Tires deteriorate with age, even if you don't use them. Either way, the rubber becomes brittle which can cause failure.

When storing your trailer, make sure the tires are not in direct sunlight (UV light oxidizes the rubber, causing the tires to rot).

The best ways to protect your tires from dry rot are to cover them and/or elevate them off the ground.

A tire pressure monitoring system (TPMS) is a group of electronic sensors placed in your tires that monitor and report air pressure in real-time. TPMS will alert you if the tire pressure becomes too low or too high based on your tire\'s load setting. The Tire Load is the amount of weight your tires can support safely. The amount of weight that can be supported is dependent on the air pressure of the tires.

The air pressure in tires impacts your vehicle\'s fuel efficiency, performance and how bumpy or smooth the vehicle feels when driving. It\'s also important to monitor tire pressure to ensure that your tires last longer and stay safe.

To set up Trailer Tire Pressure Monitoring, enter the manufacturer's recommended tire pressure.

You can find the recommended tire pressure on your trailer tire’s sidewall.

Once set, you'll receive an alert if any tire's pressure becomes too low.

It's important to charge your battery to 80% for daily use. This helps promote battery health and ensures optimal regenerative braking performance, which helps increase efficiency. For longer trips, you can adjust your charge above 80% for extended range.

If your route includes steep mountain terrain, it's important to charge to 80% or less for full regenerative braking.

Additionally, when Fast Charging, optimal speeds are achieved up to 80%.

See your Owner's Manual for more information.
Charging for Battery Health and Vehicle Safety

Just like an athlete, your battery needs a warmup to perform its best. In the same way, this feature gives your vehicle a head start for Fast Charging.\n\nWhen Fast Charging, optimal speeds are achieved between 20% and 80%. No matter your current battery level, it’s always recommended that you use this feature before plugging in at a Fast Charger.
